         <h1>Yves Congar, French Cardinal, Is Dead at 91; Vigorous Ecumenist and Promoter of the Laity </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Yves Cardinal Congar , an influential Dominican theologian whose reformist views helped to inspire Pope John XXIII and the Second Vatican Council , died on Thursday in Paris . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 91 . <br><blue>3</blue>Ordained a priest in 1930 , Pere Congar , as he was widely known throughout his life , soon became a defining force of the ecumenical movement , which had been seen as a largely Protestant enterprise . <br><blue>4</blue>In January 1936 he preached a series of sermons on the subject in Paris , and the next year he attended ecumenical conferences in Oxford , England , and Edinburgh . <br><blue>5</blue>He sustained his commitment to the movement through decades of speaking and writing . <br><blue>6</blue>Pope John Paul II honored him for his life 's work by naming him a cardinal last year . <br><blue>7</blue>It was also a formal act of forgiveness on the part of today 's conservative Vatican . <br><blue>8</blue>A prolific writer , Pere Congar was a driving force in the French worker-priest movement , which called on priests to be close to workers by living their lives . <br><blue>9</blue>The Vatican disapproved of that notion , on the ground that it distracted priests from their ecclesiastical function . <br><blue>10</blue>The Vatican held that priests risked being led into trade union affiliations and were subjected to too many secular temptations . <br><blue>11</blue>Pere Congar was severely chastized by the Vatican and fell into disgrace . <br><blue>12</blue>For two years he was forbidden to teach , lecture or publish , and he was banished to obscure posts in Jerusalem and Rome . <br><blue>13</blue>His deep unhappiness about such treatment seemed to account for what later became his extreme caution in promoting more progressive tenets in modern Catholicism . <br><blue>14</blue>But by 1960 , under Pope John XXIII , he was back in good graces and helped to shape the Second Vatican Council into a turning point for the Roman Catholic Church toward modernism . <br><blue>15</blue>After the Council , Pere Congar 's biblical and liturgical studies gained him an international reputation . <br><blue>16</blue>But by 1968 , a painful neurological ailment forced him to give up most physical activities . <br><blue>17</blue>For all his liberalism , Pere Congar opposed the marriage of priests and the annulment of Martin Luther 's excommunication for the sake of ecumenism . <br><blue>18</blue>But he strongly favored ordaining laymen " where there are no priests " and argued that some of the essential problems of the Church could be solved at the parish level . <br><blue>19</blue>Yves Marie-Joseph Congar was born in Sedan , in the Ardennes region in eastern France , the son of a bank manager . <br><blue>20</blue>After high school in Sedan , he entered a seminary in Rheims . <br><hr><br><blue>1(3)</blue>: <m_str>the Council</m_str> (15_2) 	<m_str>the Second Vatican Council</m_str> (14_20) 	<m_str>the Second Vatican Council</m_str> (1_19) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>Sedan</m_str> (20_5) 	<m_str>Sedan</m_str> (19_7) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>Paris</m_str> (4_14) 	<m_str>Paris</m_str> (1_28) 	<br><blue>4(1)</blue>: <m_str>the Church</m_str> (18_23) 	<br><blue>5(27)</blue>: <m_str>his</m_str> (3_16) 	<m_str>Pere Congar 's</m_str> (15_5) 	<m_str>Yves Marie-Joseph Congar</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_4) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (15_13) 	<m_str>Pere Congar</m_str> (8_5) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_4) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_20) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (5_3) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (16_10) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_15) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_7) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_3) 	<m_str>Pere Congar</m_str> (17_6) 	<m_str>Pope John Paul II</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (13_14) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (6_6) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (6_8) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (6_14) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (18_2) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_10) 	<m_str>Pere Congar</m_str> (3_7) 	<m_str>Pere Congar</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (3_11) 	<br><blue>6(3)</blue>: <m_str>the Vatican</m_str> (11_7) 	<m_str>The Vatican</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>The Vatican</m_str> (10_1) 	<br><blue>7(2)</blue>: <m_str>his life</m_str> (3_16) 	<m_str>his life 's</m_str> (6_8) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>their</m_str> (8_28) 	<m_str>priests</m_str> (8_20) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>it</m_str> (9_12) 	<m_str>that notion</m_str> (9_5) 	<br><blue>10(2)</blue>: <m_str>priests</m_str> (9_14) 	<m_str>their</m_str> (9_16) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
